Two moles of an ideal gas initially at $P_1 = 1.0 " atm"$ and $T_1 = 300 " K"$ undergo a three-step reversible process: (i) isobaric expansion to twice its original volume ($V_2 = 2V_1$), (ii) isothermal compression returning to the original volume ($V_3 = V_1$), and (iii) isochoric reduction in pressure back to the original state. What is the net work ($W_"net"$) done *on* the gas across the entire process?

